<doc id="198319" wikidata="Q477921" url="?curid=198319" title="Hamiltonian mechanics">
<text>In physics, Hamiltonian mechanics is a reformulation of Lagrangian mechanics that emerged in 1833. Introduced by Sir William Rowan Hamilton, Hamiltonian mechanics replaces (generalized) velocities formula_1 used in Lagrangian mechanics with (generalized) &quot;momenta&quot;. Both theories provide interpretations of classical mechanics and describe the same physical phenomena.

Hamiltonian mechanics has a close relationship with geometry (notably, symplectic geometry and Poisson structures) and serves as a link between classical and quantum mechanics.

== Overview ==
=== Phase space coordinates (&quot;p&quot;, &quot;q&quot;) and Hamiltonian &quot;H&quot; ===
Let formula_2 be a mechanical system with configuration space formula_3 and smooth Lagrangian formula_4 Select a standard coordinate system formula_5 on formula_6 The quantities formula_7 are called &quot;momenta&quot;. (Also &quot;generalized momenta&quot;, &quot;conjugate momenta&quot;, and &quot;canonical momenta&quot;). For a time instant formula_8 the Legendre transformation of formula_9 is defined as the map formula_10 which is assumed to have a smooth inverse formula_11 For a system with formula_12 degrees of freedom, the Lagrangian mechanics defines the &quot;energy function&quot;
formula_13

The Legendre transform of formula_9 turns formula_15 into a function formula_16 known as the . The Hamiltonian satisfies
formula_17
which implies that
formula_18
where the velocities formula_19 are found from the (formula_12-dimensional) equation formula_21 which, by assumption, is uniquely solvable for . The (formula_22-dimensional) pair formula_23 is called &quot;phase space coordinates&quot;. (Also &quot;canonical coordinates&quot;).

