On-shell, one substitutes parametric functions formula_58 which define a trajectory in phase space with velocities , obeying Lagrange&#x27;s equations:
formula_59

Rearranging and writing in terms of the on-shell formula_60 gives:
formula_61

Thus Lagrange&#x27;s equations are equivalent to Hamilton&#x27;s equations:
formula_62

In the case of time-independent formula_54 and , i.e. , Hamilton&#x27;s equations consist of first-order differential equations, while Lagrange&#x27;s equations consist of second-order equations. Hamilton&#x27;s equations usually do not reduce the difficulty of finding explicit solutions, but important theoretical results can be derived from them, because coordinates and momenta are independent variables with nearly symmetric roles.

Hamilton&#x27;s equations have another advantage over Lagrange&#x27;s equations: if a system has a symmetry, so that some coordinate formula_64 does not occur in the Hamiltonian (i.e. a &quot;cyclic coordinate&quot;), the corresponding momentum coordinate formula_65 is conserved along each trajectory, and that coordinate can be reduced to a constant in the other equations of the set. This effectively reduces the problem from coordinates to coordinates: this is the basis of symplectic reduction in geometry. In the Lagrangian framework, the conservation of momentum also follows immediately, however all the generalized velocities formula_66 still occur in the Lagrangian, and a system of equations in coordinates still has to be solved.

The Lagrangian and Hamiltonian approaches provide the groundwork for deeper results in classical mechanics, and suggest analogous formulations in quantum mechanics: the path integral formulation and the Schrödinger equation.

== Properties of the Hamiltonian ==
* The value of the Hamiltonian formula_67 is the total energy of the system if and only if the energy function formula_68 has the same property. (See definition of ).
* formula_69 when , form a solution of Hamilton&#x27;s equations. Indeed, formula_70 and everything but the final term cancels out.
* formula_71 does not change under &quot;point transformations&quot;, i.e. smooth changes formula_72 of space coordinates. (Follows from the invariance of the energy function formula_73 under point transformations. The invariance of formula_15 can be established directly).
* formula_75 (See &quot;).
* . (Compare Hamilton&#x27;s and Euler-Lagrange equations or see &quot;).
* formula_76 if and only if .A coordinate for which the last equation holds is called &quot;cyclic&quot; (or &quot;ignorable&quot;). Every cyclic coordinate formula_77 reduces the number of degrees of freedom by , causes the corresponding momentum formula_78 to be conserved, and makes Hamilton&#x27;s equations easier to solve.

